  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4 text-white">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
    <div class="bg-slate-900/60 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">What level of English do I need to be a flight attendant?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Most international airlines require a minimum of B2 (upper-intermediate) on the CEFR scale — roughly IELTS 5.5–6.0 or TOEIC 700+. Emirates, Qatar Airways, Etihad, and Singapore Airlines test speaking and listening during recruitment.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-slate-900/60 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How long does prep take?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300">3 to 6 months if you start at B1. Plan 15–20 speaking sessions with a tutor who knows airline interviews, plus daily listening practice and the Oxford textbook.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-slate-900/60 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Which airlines have the strictest English requirements?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Emirates, Qatar Airways, and Singapore Airlines have the toughest English screenings. British Airways and Virgin Atlantic require near-native fluency.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

    <aside class="mt-12 mb-4 p-6 bg-slate-900/60 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl">
